We use the procedure described in Sec. III to determine the uncertainty of our data projection and the uncertainty matrix. We consider both ep and eD collisions and concentrate on the two highest-energy settings listed in Table II. Because collisions with higher center-of-mass energy are more sensitive to SMEFT operators, we choose four data families with the two highest ffiffi s p to focus on:
10 GeV × 137 GeV eD 100 fb−1∶D4;ΔD4;LD4;
18 GeV × 137 GeV eD 15.4 fb−1∶D5;ΔD5;LD5;
10 GeV × 275 GeV ep 100 fb−1∶P4;ΔP4;LP4;
18 GeV × 275 GeV ep 15.4 fb−1∶P5;ΔP5;LP5:
For the highest ffiffi s p but lower-luminosity set D5, ΔD5, P5, and ΔP5, we consider two scenarios: the nominal luminosity as indicated above and in Table II, and the high luminosity option denoted with an “HL” label with tenfold higher statistics. We use Eq. (44) to generate Nexp ¼ 1000 pseudodatasets for each of the data families. We then impose the following selection criteria on the bin points, x and Q2, and the inelasticity, y:
x < 0.5; Q2 > 100 GeV2; 0.1 < y < 0.9: ð56Þ
These restrictions are designed to remove large uncertainties from nonperturbative QCD and nuclear dynamics that occur at low Q2 and high x, where sensitivity to SMEFT effects is anyway expected to be reduced. We note that the
